I am not the author, but I assume because it's nice-looking, and JavaScript already uses it for assignment (inconsistently).  Consider:<p><pre><code>   var foo = 42;

   { foo: 42 }
</code></pre>
Why make the two concepts different?<p>Also, it's "binding", not assignment.

This is nice.  There are too many gotchas to remember in JavaScript; better to let a liberal compiler translate something nice into the "machine code" that works in all browsers.<p>(Personally, I always write:<p><pre><code>   something = {
       foo: "bar",
       bar: "baz",
   }
</code></pre>
which works in Firefox, but not IE.  A compiler would not be upset when it omits that extra trailing comma.  Of course, you can always write:<p><pre><code>    something = { foo: "bar"
                , bar: "baz"
                }
</code></pre>
But let's face it, that is only not ugly in Haskell.)
